    <title>Combined summary - Simple contacts exchange (was: Social network integration (brainstorm))</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T16:41:59.897764+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-September/003235.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>There are various ways to ensure that the identity of parties involved in transactions is verified. StartSSL provides a free signed certificate by verifying an email address through a clickable link, although it may not be the most user-friendly option. However, there is no technical reason why a more usable solution cannot be developed by the competitive market for certificates.The payment protocol was designed to simplify transactions and identity verification between parties. The sender submits their own identity details, whereas the recipient vends a PaymentRequest containing theirs. There is a discussion about ways to automatically exchange contact details between wallets to encourage identifiable names and photos instead of hard-to-verify addresses. Proposed solutions include encrypting data, using fresh public keys, and Alice/Bob validating each other. Overall, the goal is to find a decentralized way to exchange contact details without compromising security or privacy.It is crucial to consider the security implications of using payment systems and take steps to protect against unauthorized access or use. One solution is to obtain a signed certificate through StartSSL, which verifies an email address through a clickable link. While not optimized for usability, there is no technical reason why one couldn't be. It is possible to set up one's own CA for the Bitcoin community and convince wallet developers to include their root cert. The payment protocol is designed to handle identity details, allowing the recipient to vend a PaymentRequest containing identity details, while the sender submits a Payment containing their own details.In a conversation between Wendell and Mike Hearn, Wendell seeks feedback on their wallet's payment protocol and expresses uncertainty about the need for signed certificates, which may hinder its adoption. Mike suggests designing a BIP to solve this issue, extending the payment protocol to include information about the person who generated it. However, Wendell raises two concerns, including the need to verify uploaded keys and securely exchange metadata beyond the scope of Bitcoin. Their aim is to road-test something quickly for the sake of user experience in their own wallet before potentially contributing to a BIP.</summary>
